In this statement, the President of the United States recognizes the International Holocaust Remembrance Day and the 70th anniversary of the liberation of Auschwitz-Birkenau. He pays tribute to the six million Jews and millions of others who were murdered by the Nazi regime. The President also honors the survivors of the Holocaust and acknowledges the challenges they have faced. He emphasizes the importance of valuing and respecting every individual and calls for the courage to protect the persecuted and speak out against bigotry and hatred. The recent terrorist attacks in Paris serve as a reminder of the need to condemn and combat rising anti-Semitism. The President reflects on the progress made in confronting the Holocaust and renews efforts to end genocide. The United States, as a founding member of the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance, reaffirms its commitment to upholding the commitments of the 2000 Stockholm Declaration. The statement concludes by pledging to never forget the victims of the Holocaust and vowing to prevent such atrocities from happening again.